 OpenVAS Demo, alternative for Nessus 
Title: Running OpenVAS for Vulnerability Scanning 
1. Setup 
• Install OpenVAS on Linux using: 
sudo apt install openvas 
• Run initial setup: 
sudo gvm-setup 
• Start OpenVAS services: 
sudo gvm-start 
2. Login 
• Open a web browser and navigate to: https://127.0.0.1:9392 
• Login with admin credentials created during setup 
3. Create Target and Task 
• Go to Targets → New Target, enter the IP address or hostname 
• Go to Tasks → New Task, select the target, and save 
4. Run Scan 
• Select the task and click Start 
• Wait for the scan to complete 
5. View Results 
• Navigate to Reports → select the latest report 
• Review the detected vulnerabilities, severity, and CVEs 
Summary: 
This process demonstrates how to use OpenVAS to perform a basic vulnerability scan, create 
targets, run tasks, and view results. 

 Alternative for Matlego 
Title: Using SpiderFoot for OSINT Recon 
1. Setup 
• Clone the repository: 
git clone https://github.com/smicallef/spiderfoot.git 
cd spiderfoot 
Install dependencies: 
python3 -m pip install -r requirements.txt 
2. Start Web UI 
• Launch SpiderFoot: 
python3 sf.py -l 127.0.0.1:5001 
• Open a web browser at: http://127.0.0.1:5001 
3. Create Scan 
• Click New Scan 
• Enter the domain or IP to investigate 
• Select modules (default is fine) and save 
4. Start Scan 
• Click Start Scan 
• Monitor progress in the web interface 
5. View Results 
• Navigate to Results 
• Explore data such as subdomains, open ports, and email addresses 
Summary: 
This demonstrates using SpiderFoot to perform automated OSINT reconnaissance, create 
and run scans, and analyse results efficiently.
